ermanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Evan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh (southern): from the personal name <i>Evan</i>, itself from <i>Ieuan</i>, a Welsh derivative of Latin <i>Johannes</i> (English <i>John</i>). See   Evans  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bevan","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Iefan</i> ‘son of Evan’, with fused patronymic marker <i>(a)p</i>. Compare   Evan   and   Evans  ."]},{"name":"Heaven","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Evan  .","English: variant of   Haven  .","Irish (Tipperary): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEimhín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eimhín</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>éimh</i> ‘swift’, ‘prompt, ready’."]},{"name":"Haven","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) harbor’, from Middle English <i>haven</i> (Old English <i>hæfen</i> ‘haven’).","Welsh (Monmouthshire): variant of   Evan  .","Dutch: variant of   Haveman  , or possibly a topographic name from <i>haven</i> ‘port, harbour’. See also   De Haven  ."]},{"name":"Evans","meanings":["Welsh: derivative of   Evan  , from <i>Efan</i>, <i>Ifan</i>, medieval forms of <i>Ieuan</i> (from Latin <i>Johannes</i>, the source of English <i>John</i>), dating from <i>c.</i> 1500, with the post-medieval patronymic suffix <i>-s</i>. Welsh <i>Sion</i> was a separate borrowing of English <i>John</i>, and <i>Evan</i> (<i>Ieuan</i>) and <i>Sion</i> developed as independent names."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan ap Evan was born about 1275, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Evan ap Howel, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. Evan ap Howel, was 24. She had at least 7 sons and 1 daughter with Howel ap Rhys Vychan ap Ioworth of Cerf-Y-Ddwy-Gwlyd."},"et":{"abt 1275–":"umbes 1275–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud"